The U.S. has the most people in jail worldwide, and Black Americans, due to historical and current racism, are locked up much more than others. In this report, I chose the last data set (a smaller dataset about prison/jail population per 100,000 people (rate) per county/state starting at 1990 in Washington) given in our homework instruction. The reason I chose this dataset is because I live in WA state and would like to know more about the incarceration in our state.

5 Variables I chose: ‘Year’; ‘Total_prison_pop’; ‘Total_jail_pop’; ‘black_jail_pop_rate’ and ‘white_jail_pop_rate’;

Summary information

5 Variables I calculated:

  1. ‘average_pop’: Calculated out the average value of population in jails of each year throughout all the WA counties. Max: 193220.3 in 2018. Min: 125719.1 in 1990

  2. ‘average_jail_pop_rate of 1990 and 2018’: Calculated out the average jail population rate at the earliest and most recent year. average_jail_pop_rate_1990 = 221.0728. average_jail_pop_rate_2018 = 326.6744

  3. ‘median_jail_pop_rate’: Calculated out the median jail rate from 1990 to 2018 throughout all WA counties. The median observation is Whatcom County in 2007 with total_jail_pop_rate = 277.89

  4. ‘highest_jail_pop_rate’: Calculated out the county with highest jail population rate throughout all WA counties in this dataset. Yakima County had the highest jail population rate 992.82 in 2007

  5. ‘average_black_rate vs. average_white_rate’: Calculated out the average jail rate for black and white people throughout counties. average_black_rate = 1868.63, average_white_rate = 261.5801; Huge difference between white and black people!!

Trends Over Time Chart:

#King county and Whatcom
two_county <- wa_pop %>%
  filter(county_name %in% c("King County", "Whatcom County"))

ggplot(data = two_county, aes(x = year, y = black_jail_pop_rate, color = county_name)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Trend of Black Jail Population in each County",
       subtitle = "(Data from 1990 to 2018)",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Black Jail Population",
       color = "County")+
theme_minimal()

I chose King County because we live here and I chose Whatcom county because it’s the median observation among all the WA counties. As we can see from the graph, King County had a lower average black jail population from 1990 to 2018. It also had smaller fluctuations in population change from year to year in overall. Since Whatcom county was the median observation in our data set (based on the median_jail_pop_rate), we can believe that King county is a relatively safe place than most of the WA Counties.

This graph shows the average jail population of the black and white people. We can still see that the black people have higher average jail population rate than white people. Based on the graph above, we can believe there is no relationship between white jail population and black jail population because their changing patterns were different (independent of each other).

To prove my conclusion correct, I made a second chart that that has White Jail Population Rate as X variable, and corresponding Black Jail Population Rate in the same year as Y variable. Even though R can draw a regression line based on these scattered points, I still believe there is no relationship between White and Black jail population rate. The distribution of the points is so random and the slope is small.

Map

#most recent year
wa_pop <- read.csv(
  "https://github.com/melaniewalsh/Neat-Datasets/raw/main/us-prison-jail-rates-1990-WA.csv"
  )

wa_pop <- wa_pop %>%
  filter(year == max(year))

wa_counties <- map_data("county", region = "washington")
wa_counties <- wa_counties %>%
  mutate(subregion = str_to_title(subregion) %>% str_c(" County"))

# Merge data
merged_data <- left_join(wa_counties, wa_pop, by = c("subregion" = "county_name"))


my_plot <- ggplot(data = merged_data, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = total_jail_pop_rate)) +
  geom_polygon() +
  coord_fixed(1) +
  labs(title = "Total Jail Population Rate of All WA Counties in 2018",
       fill = "Total Jail Rate",
       x = "Longitude",
       y = "Latitude" ) +
  scale_fill_gradient(name = "Total Jail Rate", 
                      low = "yellow", high = "red",
                      ) +
  theme_minimal()

print(my_plot)

Based on the map above, we can see that most of the counties have total jail rate around 400 in 2018. In overall, they have similar jail rates (no big difference).
